<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06150108 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06150108 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  POLAND; PRESIDENT; RELATION; ALCOHOL; BICYCLE; ABUSE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  President Lech Walesa's 18-year-old son was detained by police on amisdemeanor charge of riding his bicycle while drunk, the president'sspokesman said Tuesday.;    Przemyslaw Walesa, the second eldest of thepresident's eight children, was stopped by officers May 13 on a street in thefamily's hometown of Gdansk, police spokeswoman Maria Kazmierczak said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WALESA SON CHARGED WITH DRUNKEN BIKING  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     No date has been set for a court hearing, she said.;    According to areport in the Gdansk daily Wieczor Wybrzeza, police stopped Walesa afterwatching him weave down the street on his bicycle. A breath test registeredabove the legal limit for intoxication, the newspaper said.;    He wasreleased to the Office for Protection of the Government, which providesprotection to the president and his family, according to the report.;   Presidential spokesman Andrzej Drzycimski described &quot;Przemek&quot; as &quot;restless andfull of dynamism&quot; and said the constant guard around the family has beendifficult for him.;    &quot;Not every young man is able to accept the limitations&quot;of being the son of the president, Drzycimski said.;    The president feelsblame, the spokesman said. &quot;But at the same time he adds that everyone who haschildren knows that at some time in their lives, kids don't want to listen totheir parents' good advice, remarks or warnings.&quot;;    Walesa will &quot;not try toinfluence the case,&quot; Drzycimski said.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Warsaw, Poland  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910529  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  12A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><